{
  "doc_id": "24032",
  "text": "The decline in saccadic eye movement performance is a sensitive marker even for minor impairment of cerebral function in various physiological and pathological conditions. Sleep deprivation for 24 h has been reported to impair peak velocity of saccades and to lead to deficits of accuracy and latency [CITATION_1] . As compared to placebo, low-dose lorazepam (1-2 mg) significantly increases saccade latency and decreases peak velocity [CITATION_2] . Similar effects can be seen after consumption of moderate amounts of ethanol [CITATION_3] ). In addition, specific and marked impairment of saccadic eye movements have been reported in early Alzheimer's [CITATION_4] , mild frontotemporal dementia [CITATION_5] , and in post concussion syndrome [CITATION_6] ). To our knowledge, this is the first report on saccadic eye movements in the context of prolonged hypobaric hypoxia.",
